\begin_layout Subsubsection
Repeated Trials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Solution
\bar default
: run the basic algorithm a large number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 times, remember the smallest cut found.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Question
\bar default
: how many trials needed?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}=$
\end_inset

event that the cut 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,B)$
\end_inset

 is found on the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 try 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

by definition, different 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

's are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So.: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Pr\left[\text{all N trials fail}\right] & = & Pr[\lnot T_{1}\cap\lnot T_{2}\cap\dots\cap\lnot T_{N}]\\
(independent) & = & \prod_{i=1}^{N}Pr[\lnot T_{i}]\\
 & \le & (1-\frac{1}{n^{2}})^{N}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calculus fact: 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall$
\end_inset

 reall numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1+x\le e^{x}$
\end_inset

 [2:40].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So: if we take 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=n^{2},\, Pr\left[\text{all fail}\right]\le\left(e^{-\frac{1}{n^{2}}}\right)^{n^{2}}=\frac{1}{e}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{N=n^{2}\ln n,\, Pr\left[\text{all fail}\right]\le\left(\frac{1}{e}\right)^{\ln n}=\frac{1}{n}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Running time: Polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 but slow - 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(n^{2}m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

